so the numbers work

00:00:17.590 --> 00:00:19.760
out reasonably neat.

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:28.000
That is 4 ohms. Then I have
another resistor right here.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:36.340
That is 8 ohms. Then I have
another resistor right here.

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:43.760
That is 16 ohms. And then, I
have another resistor here,

00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:48.640
that's ohms. Actually, I'm now
making it up on the fly.

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:50.990
I think the numbers
might work out OK.

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:54.710
16 ohms.

00:00:54.710 --> 00:00:59.750
And let's say that now here in
series, I have a resistor that

00:00:59.750 --> 00:01:07.720
is 1 ohm, and then in parallel
to this whole thing-- now you

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:12.080
can see how hairy it's getting--
I have a resistor

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:22.420
that is 3 ohms. And let's say
I have a resistor here.

00:01:26.640 --> 00:01:29.650
Let's just make it
simple: 1 ohm.

00:01:29.650 --> 00:01:36.010
And just to make the numbers
reasonably easy-- I am doing

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:38.850
this on the fly now-- that's
the positive terminal,

00:01:38.850 --> 00:01:41.140
negative terminal.

00:01:41.140 --> 00:01:47.370
Let's say that the voltage
difference is 20 volts.

00:01:47.370 --> 00:01:52.050
So what I want us to do is,
figure out what is the current

00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:54.540
flowing through the wire
at that point?

00:01:54.540 --> 00:01:56.010
Obviously, that's going to be
different than the current at

00:01:56.010 --> 00:01:58.090
that point, that point, that
point, that point, all of

00:01:58.090 --> 00:01:59.710
these different points, but it's
going to be the same as

00:01:59.710 --> 00:02:01.880
the current flowing
at this point.

00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:03.370
So what is I?

00:02:03.370 --> 00:02:05.920
So the easiest way to do this
is try to figure out the

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:07.040
equivalent resistance.

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:09.199
Because once we know the
equivalent resistance of this

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:12.940
big hairball, then we can just
use Ohm's law and be done.

00:02:12.940 --> 00:02:16.460
So first of all, let's just
start at, I could argue, the

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:17.090
simplest part.

00:02:17.090 --> 00:02:19.310
Let's see if we could figure out
the equivalent resistance

00:02:19.310 --> 00:02:23.550
of these four resistors
in parallel.

00:02:23.550 --> 00:02:26.160
Well, we know that that
resistance is going to be

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:34.800
equal to 1/4 plus 1/8
plus 1/16 plus 1/16.

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:37.450
So that resistance-- and
now it's just adding

00:02:37.450 --> 00:02:39.100
fractions-- over 16.

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:48.740
1/4 is 4/16 plus 2/16 plus 1
plus 1, so 1/R is equal to 4

00:02:48.740 --> 00:02:53.170
plus 2 is equal to 8/16-- the
numbers are working out-- is

00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:57.260
equal to 1/2, so that equivalent
resistance is 2.

00:02:57.260 --> 00:02:59.490
So that, quickly, we just
said, well, all of these

00:02:59.490 --> 00:03:04.110
